export function DuckEssay() {
  return (
    <div className="space-y-4 text-foreground/75 leading-7">
      <p>
        Programmers explain their problem to a rubber duck. The duck knows
        nothing. Can&apos;t help. And yet, articulating a problem out loud — to
        something that won&apos;t interrupt, won&apos;t agree, won&apos;t
        suggest — finds the bug roughly half the time.
      </p>
      <p>
        The trick is that the duck doesn&apos;t pretend. The verification was
        never coming from the duck. It was coming from the act of articulation,
        the speaking-into-form that forces an idea to be specific enough to be
        wrong.
